english:
  title: A Curse Upon the Rats, with Preface
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Our household has never kept a cat, and so the rat-swarms run rampant and unbridled. Despising this pestilence, I curse them now.

    Consider: in a human dwelling, the grandfather and grandmother hold honored station, and those who assist them each bear their appointed duties. The servant who tends the kitchen wears red feet; the servant who tends the woodcutter's work is Kunlun himself. Down to the six beasts, each has its station and sphere. The horse bears our burdens, carries and gallops; the ox draws heavy loads and breaks the soil; the rooster crows to herald dawn; the dog barks to guard the gate—all fulfill their roles to serve the master alone.

    But I ask you, rats: what duty is yours? Who deemed you worthy of this dwelling? From where did you spring and multiply? You alone know the art of gnawing through walls and thieving. True robbers come from without, yet you dwell within and betray the house itself! You honeycomb the walls with holes, darting in and out, scurrying mad in the darkness, scratching all night long. When sleep comes, your insolence doubles; you parade in broad daylight—from chamber to kitchen, from hall to study. Even the vessels for Buddha and the offerings to the gods you defile and desecrate first, showing contempt for the sacred and the divine. Yet you bore through the hardest wood and slip into sealed chests and boxes, ever tunneling, ever breaking through, smoke seeping from every corner of your passage.

    Yes, you steal food like common thieves, and for this I say nothing—fill your bellies if you must. But why do you gnaw our garments to tatters, rendering them unwearable? Why do you chew the silk threads, spoiling the fabric? Why this pointless destruction?

    Your master should be the cat. Have I not the means to keep one? It is only that mercy dwells in my nature, and I have not the heart to inflict such cruelty. But you show no gratitude for this forbearance—you dash about, you collide, you persist in your chaos. Take this warning to heart and repent! Flee swiftly from my house. Otherwise, I shall unleash the fierce cat upon you, and in a single day your entire clan shall be slaughtered. The cat's mouth shall be smeared with your grease, the cat's belly shall be your tomb. Though you long for resurrection, no ransom can restore your lives. Go now! Go at once! Swift as the urgency of sacred law, depart!
  footnotes:
    - 赤脚 (Red Foot) and 崑崙 (Kunlun) are poetic names for household servants—the former a female servant, the latter a male servant.
    - 'The ''six beasts'' (六畜) refers to the traditional livestock of East Asian households: horse, ox, sheep, pig, dog, and chicken.'
    - The closing phrase '急急如律令' (swift as sacred law) is a common formulaic ending in Chinese curse inscriptions and magical texts, lending the curse an official or liturgical authority.
